1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,840
 So now let's design a data model.

2
00:00:02,840 --> 00:00:07,160
 Usually you start out with a user interface

3
00:00:07,160 --> 00:00:09,540
 that if we're gonna build an application,

4
00:00:09,540 --> 00:00:12,040
 you're gonna end up with a user interface.

5
00:00:12,040 --> 00:00:14,280
 In this, I'm not gonna really start with a user interface.

6
00:00:14,280 --> 00:00:16,840
 I'm gonna start with like a spreadsheet view.

7
00:00:16,840 --> 00:00:19,840
 And if you've ever done something like tried to

8
00:00:19,840 --> 00:00:22,000
 organize your music collection with a spreadsheet

9
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:24,360
 or a video collection with a spreadsheet,

10
00:00:24,360 --> 00:00:28,600
 or you know, you find that spreadsheets are super convenient

11
00:00:28,600 --> 00:00:30,520
 because you can scroll around and do stuff

12
00:00:30,520 --> 00:00:32,360
 and you know, you've learned SQL,

13
00:00:32,360 --> 00:00:35,320
 you know you can go into various cells with SQL,

14
00:00:35,320 --> 00:00:38,400
 rows and columns and update and do all this stuff.

15
00:00:38,400 --> 00:00:40,800
 But you find that after a while,

16
00:00:40,800 --> 00:00:43,960
 you start repeating yourself in spreadsheets

17
00:00:43,960 --> 00:00:45,400
 and you find it's really difficult

18
00:00:45,400 --> 00:00:47,480
 because it's really easy when you're putting data into

19
00:00:47,480 --> 00:00:50,360
 copy, paste, copy, paste, paste, paste, paste, paste, paste,

20
00:00:50,360 --> 00:00:51,520
 and put the same stuff in.

21
00:00:51,520 --> 00:00:53,240
 But then what if you wanna change it?

22
00:00:53,240 --> 00:00:55,240
 And this is where there's a vertical replication

23
00:00:55,240 --> 00:00:58,160
 or the replication of data in multiple places

24
00:00:58,160 --> 00:00:59,000
 is very bad.

25
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:02,240
 So here's kind of an exploded table view of that same data.

26
00:01:02,240 --> 00:01:04,560
 And this is, it's okay.

27
00:01:04,560 --> 00:01:06,520
 This is the data that we've gotta do.

28
00:01:06,520 --> 00:01:10,760
 So if we look at the use cases of our application,

29
00:01:10,760 --> 00:01:13,360
 what we see is there's a series of books,

30
00:01:13,360 --> 00:01:15,520
 like in this course, Wisdom of Crowds is a book,

31
00:01:15,520 --> 00:01:17,400
 Introduction to Networking, these are all books

32
00:01:17,400 --> 00:01:19,800
 coming down here, unlocking the clubhouse.

33
00:01:19,800 --> 00:01:21,720
 So the first column is titles of books.

34
00:01:21,720 --> 00:01:23,880
 The second column is the ISBN.

35
00:01:23,880 --> 00:01:25,960
 And then we are sort of keeping track

36
00:01:25,960 --> 00:01:28,160
 because we're a library and so we might have more than

37
00:01:28,160 --> 00:01:31,440
 one book and we're gonna call those the book instance.

38
00:01:31,440 --> 00:01:34,120
 So instance one, instance two, instance three.

39
00:01:34,120 --> 00:01:37,640
 Each book, each physical actual book so that

40
00:01:37,640 --> 00:01:39,960
 you might have no physical books actually,

41
00:01:39,960 --> 00:01:42,440
 or you might have one physical book or five physical books

42
00:01:42,440 --> 00:01:44,720
 and each physical book might be checked out

43
00:01:44,720 --> 00:01:47,120
 and have a due date and so we have a status.

44
00:01:47,120 --> 00:01:49,240
 And then we have something like say the language of the book

45
00:01:49,240 --> 00:01:51,720
 or the genre of the book or who wrote the book, right?

46
00:01:51,720 --> 00:01:55,640
 And so that's kind of our, the data we're going to

47
00:01:55,640 --> 00:01:59,040
 represent in this application.

48
00:01:59,040 --> 00:02:02,000
 Now, when you're looking at this,

49
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:04,080
 the first thing you do is you go like,

50
00:02:04,080 --> 00:02:07,660
 anything where you've got vertical replication is a problem.

51
00:02:07,660 --> 00:02:09,800
 And so you've gotta be careful so you look for

52
00:02:09,800 --> 00:02:12,960
 vertical replication and the places that are problematic

53
00:02:12,960 --> 00:02:15,440
 in this table view of all of our data,

54
00:02:15,440 --> 00:02:18,560
 like the status, the language, the genre,

55
00:02:18,560 --> 00:02:20,560
 you see the word think, think, think, think, think.

56
00:02:20,560 --> 00:02:21,920
 Those are strings, right?

57
00:02:21,920 --> 00:02:23,240
 They're not numbers.

58
00:02:23,240 --> 00:02:25,920
 Okay, wisdom of crowds, wisdom of crowds, wisdom of crowds.

59
00:02:25,920 --> 00:02:28,560
 And the problem here with wisdom of crowds

60
00:02:28,560 --> 00:02:31,120
 is that there are three instances of the book,

61
00:02:31,120 --> 00:02:34,760
 but then because we've got this all in one row,

62
00:02:34,760 --> 00:02:36,920
 I mean one table with just a bunch of columns

63
00:02:36,920 --> 00:02:40,020
 and not multiple tables, well, we have to replicate

64
00:02:40,020 --> 00:02:42,240
 the name wisdom of crowds three times

65
00:02:42,240 --> 00:02:44,620
 so that we can represent the three instances.

66
00:02:44,620 --> 00:02:46,400
 The same is true about the English language

67
00:02:46,400 --> 00:02:49,220
 and the genre and the author name, right?

68
00:02:49,220 --> 00:02:51,980
 These are the same authors, okay?

69
00:02:51,980 --> 00:02:54,860
 So this vertical replication is your first clue

70
00:02:54,860 --> 00:02:57,640
 that says that you've got to come up

71
00:02:57,640 --> 00:03:00,880
 with a smarter data model than just this.

72
00:03:00,880 --> 00:03:03,400
 And so the idea is is you're not allowed

73
00:03:03,400 --> 00:03:06,600
 to put something like the string en, English,

74
00:03:06,600 --> 00:03:09,080
 in more than once in your whole database.

75
00:03:09,080 --> 00:03:11,400
 So what you have to do is you have to split this all out.

76
00:03:11,400 --> 00:03:13,720
 Somehow, you have to remove duplication

77
00:03:13,720 --> 00:03:16,680
 by making a language table, a book table,

78
00:03:16,680 --> 00:03:18,200
 and an instance table.

79
00:03:18,200 --> 00:03:21,940
 And so in the book table, you only put wisdom of crowds once

80
00:03:21,940 --> 00:03:23,840
 and you only put the English language in once

81
00:03:23,840 --> 00:03:25,640
 and Spanish in once.

82
00:03:25,640 --> 00:03:29,560
 But then the problem is, okay, somehow we've taken this data

83
00:03:29,560 --> 00:03:32,800
 and moved it from one big, long bunch of columns

84
00:03:32,800 --> 00:03:34,600
 to three tables with sets of columns.

85
00:03:34,600 --> 00:03:37,280
 But we still have to represent all the original data

86
00:03:37,280 --> 00:03:38,440
 that we were working with before.

87
00:03:38,440 --> 00:03:40,240
 We have to represent all that stuff.

88
00:03:40,240 --> 00:03:44,460
 And so this is where we have to be able to make connections.

89
00:03:44,460 --> 00:03:47,500
 And this is the essence of relational databases

90
00:03:47,500 --> 00:03:50,880
 and that is they don't replicate data,

91
00:03:50,880 --> 00:03:53,780
 but they make connections from one data item

92
00:03:53,780 --> 00:03:55,240
 to another data item.

93
00:03:55,240 --> 00:03:57,440
 And so what we're gonna do here is in the case

94
00:03:57,440 --> 00:04:00,440
 of the wisdom of crowds, we are going to have

95
00:04:00,440 --> 00:04:04,160
 three book instances, but somehow they all point

96
00:04:04,160 --> 00:04:08,200
 to one book in the book table, right?

97
00:04:08,200 --> 00:04:11,920
 And so we have two books that point to the English language

98
00:04:11,920 --> 00:04:14,160
 and one points to the Spanish language.

99
00:04:14,160 --> 00:04:17,580
 Now this seems like, wow, that wasn't such a big deal.

100
00:04:17,580 --> 00:04:19,680
 But when you do millions of records, it actually matters.

101
00:04:19,680 --> 00:04:22,120
 It's the string data that gets you in trouble

102
00:04:22,120 --> 00:04:24,960
 and requires far more scanning and far more storage.

103
00:04:24,960 --> 00:04:27,520
 And another thing that happens is when you follow

104
00:04:27,520 --> 00:04:30,640
 this rule of only one copy, well what if we wanted

105
00:04:30,640 --> 00:04:33,600
 to turn this to uppercase EN or something?

106
00:04:33,600 --> 00:04:36,160
 That means as long as the data is linked

107
00:04:36,160 --> 00:04:38,820
 rather than replicated, that means you're only changing

108
00:04:38,820 --> 00:04:40,520
 one copy, okay?

109
00:04:40,520 --> 00:04:43,760
 So the replication has a performance advantage,

110
00:04:43,760 --> 00:04:47,460
 has a storage advantage, and it has a modifiability advantage

111
00:04:47,460 --> 00:04:49,480
 when there's only one place.

112
00:04:49,480 --> 00:04:53,260
 If we mistakenly misspelled the title of wisdom of crowds,

113
00:04:53,260 --> 00:04:55,000
 it's easy, we fix it.

114
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:56,480
 It's not in these other tables.

115
00:04:56,480 --> 00:04:58,880
 Whereas if we misspelled the wisdom of crowds here,

116
00:04:58,880 --> 00:05:01,320
 we have to go find on the top one where it's just

117
00:05:01,320 --> 00:05:04,160
 all one big long spreadsheet, we gotta go and like

118
00:05:04,160 --> 00:05:07,360
 do a search and replace, but what if that's

119
00:05:07,360 --> 00:05:08,520
 in a different column?

120
00:05:08,520 --> 00:05:13,120
 So the idea of getting to the point where we have

121
00:05:13,120 --> 00:05:16,180
 unique rows and we connect those rows.

122
00:05:16,180 --> 00:05:19,360
 Now, I haven't told you much about how this magically works.

123
00:05:19,360 --> 00:05:21,620
 I just said we can draw some arrows,

124
00:05:21,620 --> 00:05:24,080
 and so by drawing those arrows, we gotta show you

125
00:05:24,080 --> 00:05:27,320
 how those arrows get drawn, 'cause that's really important.

126
00:05:27,320 --> 00:05:30,240
 So this is how you start drawing the picture

127
00:05:30,240 --> 00:05:34,680
 of your database, and so the kind of relationship

128
00:05:34,680 --> 00:05:37,520
 we're gonna have between tables is like a many to one.

129
00:05:37,520 --> 00:05:41,080
 So when we say many to one, what we're saying is that

130
00:05:41,080 --> 00:05:44,480
 there is one English language entry,

131
00:05:44,480 --> 00:05:47,240
 and then there are many books that go to it.

132
00:05:47,240 --> 00:05:49,160
 So that's a many to one relationship.

133
00:05:49,160 --> 00:05:53,160
 So it could be just one, but it's many.

134
00:05:53,160 --> 00:05:55,640
 And if we look at the data model that we see

135
00:05:55,640 --> 00:06:00,360
 from the Django example from the Mozilla Developer Network,

136
00:06:00,360 --> 00:06:03,400
 we can look at this and we can see here, right?

137
00:06:03,400 --> 00:06:07,320
 This connection between the book table and the language table

138
00:06:07,320 --> 00:06:10,960
 has two ends to it, and it has a direction to it,

139
00:06:10,960 --> 00:06:13,680
 and one end says zero dot dot asterisk,

140
00:06:13,680 --> 00:06:15,700
 and the other end says one.

141
00:06:15,700 --> 00:06:19,820
 So this is many, zero dot dot asterisk means

142
00:06:19,820 --> 00:06:23,060
 a number between zero and infinity, including zero,

143
00:06:23,060 --> 00:06:24,640
 which means it's possible for a book

144
00:06:24,640 --> 00:06:26,600
 not to have a language, we call that.

145
00:06:26,600 --> 00:06:28,840
 We call that null in database concept.

146
00:06:28,840 --> 00:06:31,180
 So there's a book with no language,

147
00:06:31,180 --> 00:06:34,320
 or many books can have one language.

148
00:06:34,320 --> 00:06:38,020
 So there's one language, English, and there is

149
00:06:38,020 --> 00:06:41,920
 as many books as we want, including potentially zero books.

150
00:06:41,920 --> 00:06:45,160
 So we might have a language that has no books

151
00:06:45,160 --> 00:06:47,920
 in our library with that language, and that's okay.

152
00:06:47,920 --> 00:06:52,040
 So in this one, between book and language,

153
00:06:52,040 --> 00:06:53,720
 it's okay to have zero.

154
00:06:53,720 --> 00:06:57,760
 So zero through infinity on the book side of the relationship

155
00:06:57,760 --> 00:07:00,480
 and one on the language side of the relationship.

156
00:07:00,480 --> 00:07:04,160
 If then we look at the relationship

157
00:07:04,160 --> 00:07:08,680
 between the book and the book instance,

158
00:07:08,680 --> 00:07:10,760
 now remember what the book instance purpose is

159
00:07:10,760 --> 00:07:13,420
 is to record the fact that we have multiple copies.

160
00:07:13,420 --> 00:07:16,800
 The actual physical copies of the books that we have.

161
00:07:16,800 --> 00:07:19,000
 And so we might have multiple copies.

162
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:22,400
 And so if you look at this, it's pretty much the same

163
00:07:22,400 --> 00:07:26,640
 in that there is any number of book instances

164
00:07:26,640 --> 00:07:31,560
 from zero until infinities, and you could have a book

165
00:07:31,560 --> 00:07:34,480
 in your book table for which you didn't actually

166
00:07:34,480 --> 00:07:36,280
 own a physical copy, and that'd be okay.

167
00:07:36,280 --> 00:07:38,400
 We would know things like what its author was,

168
00:07:38,400 --> 00:07:41,160
 what its genre was, et cetera, and then we would

169
00:07:41,160 --> 00:07:44,080
 buy a copy of said book, and we'd add a copy

170
00:07:44,080 --> 00:07:46,120
 to the instance table, and then we'd link that

171
00:07:46,120 --> 00:07:47,120
 into that book.

172
00:07:47,120 --> 00:07:50,540
 So again, you can have zero book instances,

173
00:07:50,540 --> 00:07:53,240
 well, zero through infinity book instances

174
00:07:53,240 --> 00:07:56,360
 mapped to a single book entry.

175
00:07:56,360 --> 00:07:58,840
 Okay, and so this little legend, you know,

176
00:07:58,840 --> 00:08:03,840
 zero to infinity to one, is how we read this table.

177
00:08:03,840 --> 00:08:07,000
 And you will see database tables

178
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:09,860
 that have different syntaxes, but they all are capturing

179
00:08:09,860 --> 00:08:12,320
 the same thing, and that's the cardinality,

180
00:08:12,320 --> 00:08:15,060
 or the number of things at each end of the arrow.

181
00:08:15,060 --> 00:08:17,840
 So up next, we're gonna show you how to actually

182
00:08:17,840 --> 00:08:19,960
 physically store this information in the database.

183
00:08:19,960 --> 00:08:21,640
 So far, I've been just sort of saying,

184
00:08:21,640 --> 00:08:24,120
 and there's an arrow, but we have to have a way

185
00:08:24,120 --> 00:08:26,080
 to actually store it in the database.

186
00:08:26,080 --> 00:08:28,500
 (jazz music)

